Cooper Neill is a photojournalist based out of Dallas, Texas and is starting his 5th year with the NFL Focus team this season. Cooper has worked with many notable companies, including; The New York Times, UFC, ESPN, NBA, the Wall Street Journal, and more.

Looking back, what and/or who first inspired you to pursue sports photography?

  My journey into photography is probably a little different from most... I tried out to be a photographer for my high school yearbook and was told I wasn’t good enough and pretty much gave up photography on the spot. Five or six years later, I was in college and realized I could get into concerts for free around Nashville if I showed up with a camera. From there, it became a fun way to get some beer money while I was finishing up my degree and eventually, I decided it would be a fun thing to pursue full-time. So, I moved from Nashville to Austin and got my masters degree in journalism. After a few internships, I ended up at the Dallas Morning News. I eventually left because I wanted to do less sports and more long-form documentary projects but I kept getting calls to cover sporting events and it snowballed from there.

How many years have you been covering sports? And what are some of the obstacles you’ve faced along the way?

  I’ve been covering sports pretty regularly for the last 15 years, starting back when I was in college. One of the toughest obstacles in sports photography is just keeping your creative juices flowing each game and really focusing on making something unique every time you’re out there. It doesn’t matter if it’s football, basketball, baseball, etc., if you’re working those events enough, it’s easy to get in a rut when you’re extremely limited on shooting positions, the lighting and everyone is using the same gear. It takes a conscious effort to move around, bring some different gear you haven’t used in a while and be ok with possibly missing something so you can get something new.
